We start by noting the key items from the statements:

1. Owner’s Equity  
• Beginning Owner’s Equity (from balance sheet at the start): 28,000,000.00  
• Ending Owner’s Equity (Paid-in Capital + Retained Earnings at end): 28,000,000.00 + 1,250,911.98 = 29,250,911.98  
• Average Owner’s Equity = (28,000,000.00 + 29,250,911.98) / 2 = 28,625,455.99

2. Net Profit (from income statement) = 1,250,911.98

3. Total Assets (end) = 31,154,033.87

4. Total Liabilities (end)  
• Here the only liabilities given are current liabilities (Accounts Payable + Taxes Payable) = 1,000,000.00 + 903,121.89 = 1,903,121.89

5. Gross Profit and Total Revenue (from income statement)  
• Gross Profit = 4,962,437.45  
• Total Revenue = 18,062,437.45

Now compute each metric:

A. Return on Equity (ROE):  
ROE = (Net Profit / Average Owner’s Equity) × 100  
   = (1,250,911.98 / 28,625,455.99) × 100  
   ≈ 4.37%

B. Debt to Asset Ratio:  
Debt to Asset Ratio = Total Liabilities / Total Assets  
   = 1,903,121.89 / 31,154,033.87  
   ≈ 0.0611  
We express this as 0.06 (rounded to two decimal places).

C. Gross Profit Margin:  
Gross Profit Margin = (Gross Profit / Total Revenue) × 100  
   = (4,962,437.45 / 18,062,437.45) × 100  
   ≈ 27.47%

Thus, the final answer is:

{
  "solution": {
    "Return on Equity (ROE)": "4.37%",
    "Debt to Asset Ratio": "0.06",
    "Gross Profit Margin": "27.47%"
  }
}
